	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>In order to better analyze Thott's postings on The Shaman's Crucible, I created a simulation of his effect on crucible readers:<br />
<br />
<br />
<img src="http://www.bright.net/~jstorch/thottless.jpg" border="0" alt=""> <br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Thott’s Credibility (Green)</b> – Our graph starts about midrange.  The data modeler added points for him being guild leader of Afterlife who invented DKP and the metric system.  It added points his name being <i>like</i> the word “thought” but subtracted more for being misspelled.  Additional points for using PHP instead of ASP.<br />
<br />
As we progress the simulation, we see his Credibility Factor (CF) begin to slide as people actually look at his charts.  The modeler internally assigns the term “crack monkey smoking?” to some of the sharper declinations.  The CF falls again when simulated readers realize he is a bard.  I had to filter some spurious noise when parts of the simulation got stuck in “what does a bard guild leader actually do?” and “aren’t they all girls?” loops.<br />
<br />
There are few momentary spikes in the CF when sim-Thott appears to respond to comments made by actual sim-shaman but falls again as sim-Thott is unnaturally resistant to ‘applied learning’.  About mid-way readers remember Thott’s first visit where he calls them a bunch of purple-faced babies for <i>thinking</i> about an AE slow because AE slow is the GOD GIVEN EXCLUSIVE DOMAIN OF BARDS ™.  Sim-Thott deletes this post trying to maintain his “oh, I spent 27 man hours on this just out of boredom” premise.  Couple more filters added as sim-readers got stuck on “bards can slow?” loops.        <br />
<br />
Towards the end of the data crunching CF bottoms-out as sim-readers from sim-Caster’s Realm demand that shaman shouldn’t be permitted to stack Canni 1 – 4 and must stop soloing Guardian Gorenaires with their zero aggro dots.  CF is pretty much zero as sim-Thott comments that of course his chart has no relevance to the actual game while posting links on a few more message boards.<br />
<br />
<b>Thott’s Efficiency (red)</b> – Our modeling begins pretty low as sim-Thott is busy creating simulations with level 39 clerics, level 43 druids, and level 97 shaman. A median value is assigned as Thott could have pressed “play manasong” on his second PC.  He does save some time by reusing large segments of his “Olsen Twins vs. Mechagodzilla” sim from band camp but then additional efficiency is lost as sim-Thott babbles into a Barbie phone, “Was Furor there?  Did he mention me? <a href="http://www.afterlifeguild.org/Thott/bard_pulling.php" target="_blank">That thing he did with the monks was SHWEEET</a>!" <br />
<br />
<br />
Later, we see a huge rise as Thott has some guildmates power level him to 65.  We assume he plays manasong constantly.<br />
<br />
<b>Thott’s Ego (blue)</b> – Pretty constant across the board.  The negative values generated from having 8th grade math students drive 350 ton Terex Dumptrucks through his charts are offset by the all attention generated for him and not those sluts from FoH.  Rises more as he skips tap class to level to 65.<br />
<br />
Conclusion?<br />
<br />
We have a running joke at my work that if you make a CHART then people cannot possibly refute what you say.  I see a person who got called misinformed by a class forum go and spend a great deal of time creating some very skewed data in hopes of nerfing players because they <i>argued</i> with him.  Why would someone do this?  Because all their feelings of self worth come from who they are within a game.<br />
<br />
Edit: Fixed typo and censored stuff that might conflict with my agenda</p>
	
	
	
	
	
